<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-785-154  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 785 154.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  August 20 1990 v16 n16 p21(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Report finds U.S. losing lead in emerging technologies. (TheCommerce Department's Office of Technology Administration)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Department of Commerce Office of Technology Administrationissues a report on emerging technologies that indicates the US islosing its lead in several critical technologies, includingelectronics, to Japan and Europe.andP;  Twelve technologies with acombined potential market of $350 billion in the US and $1trillion worldwide by the year 2000 were identified by the reportas critical to the future of US materials, electronics,manufacturing and life sciences.andP;  The electronics categoryincludes advanced semiconductors, digital imaging technology,high-density storage, high-performance computing andoptoelectronics; it will be worth $150 billion in the US and $350billion worldwide by the year 2000, according to the report.andP;  Theincreased spending on research and development in Japan is citedas a primary reason for the projected loss of US leadership in keytechnologies; 13 remedies were proposed by the report to reversethe deterioration of US technology development.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic IndustryOutlookInternationalCompetitionNational GovernmentGovernment AgencyReportsForecastingUnited States. Department of Commerce. Office of TechnologyAdministration.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   The U.S. gets a D on its technology report card. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>